{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505557"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:32:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:32:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2454"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2454"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.57,0.26,0.08,0.07,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2454"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102226"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2454"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2454"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84690"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1638"},{"type":"tags","id":"4090"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2009"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2029"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8691"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35240"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43158"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102226","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102226"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with worsening pelvic pain and heavy menstrual bleeding for the past 12 months. The pain is described as dull, achy and comes and goes spontaneously. She reports that her menstrual cycle occurs at a 28-day interval with each period lasting seven days. Her menstrual flow has been consistently heavy over the past 12 months, requiring six to seven pads of moderate strength each day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She has never been pregnant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears comfortable with vital signs within normal limits. On pelvic examination, the uterus is firm, enlarged and irregular in shape. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. Her urine pregnancy test is negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA pelvic ultrasound reveals a 3 cm hypoechoic mass distorting the endometrial cavity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following types of uterine fibroid is most likely present in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Submucosal fibroid","Intramural fibroid","Subserosal fibroid","Subserosal Pedunculated fibroid","Cervical fibroid"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with heavy menstrual bleeding and pelvic pain with an ultrasound showing a hypoechoic mass distorting the endometrial cavity. These findings are most consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Esubmucosal fibroid\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubmucosal fibroids\u003C/strong\u003E develop beneath the endometrium (the inner lining of the uterus) and protrude into the uterine cavity. They are strongly associated with heavy menstrual bleeding because they increase the surface area of the endometrium and can interfere with the normal contractility of the uterus during menstruation. The distortion of the endometrial cavity seen on ultrasound is characteristic of submucosal fibroids. Importantly, the classification of fibroid type impacts treatment options. Submucosal fibroids are amenable to hysteroscopic resection, whereas other types of fibroids generally require different surgical approaches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramural fibroids\u003C/strong\u003E are located within the myometrium (the muscular wall of the uterus) and are the most common type of fibroid. While they can cause heavy bleeding, especially if they distort the uterine cavity, they typically do not directly protrude into the endometrial cavity as described in this case. They may cause a more diffuse enlargement of the uterus rather than a discrete mass distorting the cavity. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubserosal fibroids\u003C/strong\u003E develop beneath the serosa (the outer covering of the uterus) and grow outward from the uterus. They typically cause pressure symptoms such as urinary frequency or constipation rather than heavy menstrual bleeding. They would not distort the endometrial cavity as seen in this case. Subserosal fibroids are not accessible via hysteroscopy and require laparoscopic or open surgical approaches if treatment is needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubserosal Pedunculated fibroids\u003C/strong\u003E are attached to the uterus by a stalk or pedicle and can be either submucosal (projecting into the uterine cavity) or subserosal (projecting outward from the uterus). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical fibroids\u003C/strong\u003E develop in the cervix rather than the body of the uterus. They are relatively uncommon and typically cause symptoms related to pressure on the bladder or rectum, or dyspareunia. They would not distort the endometrial cavity of the uterine body as described in this case. Cervical fibroids present unique surgical challenges and are not amenable to standard hysteroscopic techniques.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Submucosal fibroids are most strongly associated with heavy menstrual bleeding due to their location beneath the endometrium.","Intramural fibroids are the most common type, located within the myometrium, and can cause both heavy bleeding and pelvic pressure.","Subserosal fibroids grow outward from the uterus and primarily cause pressure symptoms rather than bleeding abnormalities."],"references":["Stewart EA, Cookson CL, Gandolfo RA, Schulze-Rath R. Epidemiology of uterine fibroids: a systematic review. BJOG 2017; 124:1501.","Wise LA, Laughlin-Tommaso SK. Epidemiology of Uterine Fibroids: From Menarche to Menopause. Clin Obstet Gynecol 2016; 59:2.","Palheta MS, Medeiros FDC, Severiano ARG. Reporting of uterine fibroids on ultrasound examinations: an illustrated report template focused on surgical planning. Radiol Bras. 2023 Mar-Apr;56(2):86-94. doi: 10.1590/0100-3984.2022.0048. PMID: 37168038; PMCID: PMC10165971."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84690"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2454"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84690"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-10T21:50:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-11T08:35:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2454"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102226"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{